<Author>IanWriter
<Content>Colorful gay hotel This place is a trip in itself! First, you need to forget all notions of a hotel as a separate, purpose built structure. This hotel is converted from what must have been an enormous apartment on the third floor of a pre-war luxury apartment building. So the entire hotel is on one level, with the very high ceilings typical of similar buildings of that era. The art in the hotel name refers to the paintings -- consisting mostly of, uh, male figurative art -- that cover the walls. No two rooms are the same. Some of the original rooms have been subdivided and most have had bathrooms (necessarily small) added. Each room has TV with local channels plus CNN and BBC, a telephone, and a mini bar with a few items. Each room is a different color, and we are not talking beige and cream here, but rather scarlet, cobalt, daffodil, etc. The furniture is likewise electic; a lot of it appears to be older pieces repainted in black or lavender to smarten things up. The hotel website includes pictures of each room so you can see what you are getting. A wireless connection is available in the rooms if you want to use your own laptop; if not, there is also a computer for guest use. The front office is attended rather sporadically but you get three keys for the duration of your stay: one of the building entrance, one for the hotel entrance, and one for your room. There is an ample German-continental breakfast included in the price of the room. Staff members I encountered included a striking gentleman in full leather outfit, and a gracious youth in more conventional attire. And yes, the floors creak and the public lighting is dim. The hotel is very well located for Berlin's gay Sch枚neberg district, and there is even a gay bar/club/cafe complex on the first floor of the building. Literature on gay Berlin with maps, etc, is in the rooms too. If you must have the predictability of Holiday Inns and Hilton Hotels, or if you are a complainer or whiner, this place is not for you. Its too eccentric. If you can take an amiable and oddball experience like this in your stride, go there -- its a blast! 
